<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ861203-0176 </DOCNO><HL>  </HL><SO>  </SO><IN> FRESTMONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON) </IN><DATELINE> WELLINGTON, New Zealand  </DATELINE><TEXT>   Aided by an improvement in the merchandise-trade balance, New Zealand's deficit on its current account narrowed to the equivalent of $100.5 million in October from $194.4 million in September, the Statistics Department said.    The current account comprises merchandise trade, trade in services and some unilateral transfers.    In merchandise trade alone, New Zealand posted an October surplus of $14 million, in contrast to a deficit of $63.6 million in the prior month. Exports fell 9.6% from September, to $491.5 million, while imports declined 21%, to $477.6 million. </TEXT></DOC>